<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<handout>
  <title>Worksheet 2.3, Invertible Matrices</title>

  <ul marker="">

    <li workspace="2in">
      <p>(1) &#160; Indicate whether the statements are true or false. <m>A</m> is an <m>n \times n</m> matrix.</p>
      <ol marker="(a)">
        <li>
          <p>If <m>A\vec{x} = A\vec{y}</m> for some <m>\vec{x} \ne \vec{y}</m> in <m>\mathbb{R}^n</m>,
          then <m>A</m> cannot be invertible.</p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>If for some <m>\vec{b} \in \mathbb{R}^n</m>, the equation <m>A\vec{x} = \vec{b}</m> has more than one solution,
          then <m>A</m> is invertible.</p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>Every elementary matrix is invertible.</p>
        </li>
      </ol>
    </li>

    <li workspace="2in">
      <p>(2) &#160; Let <m>A</m> be an <m>n \times n</m> matrix. Which statements guarantee that <m>A</m> is invertible?</p>
      <ol marker="(a)">
        <li><p>Every vector in <m>\mathbb{R}^n</m> is in the span of the columns of <m>A</m>.</p></li>
        <li><p><m>A\vec{x} = \vec{b}</m> has a solution for every <m>\vec{b} \in \mathbb{R}^n</m>.</p></li>
        <li><p>The matrix <m>A</m> can be row‑reduced to the identity matrix.</p></li>
        <li><p>The range of the linear transformation <m>\vec{x} \mapsto A\vec{x}</m> is <m>\mathbb{R}^n</m>.</p></li>
      </ol>
    </li>

    <li workspace="2in">
      <p>(3) &#160; Two reasons that a matrix is not invertible are:</p>
      <ol marker="(a)">
        <li><p>one column is a multiple of another column</p></li>
        <li><p>one column is the sum of other columns</p></li>
      </ol>
      <p>By inspection, identify which of the reasons above apply to the following matrices.</p>

      <p>
        <me>
        A =
        \begin{pmatrix}
          0 &amp; 1 &amp; 1 \\
          2 &amp; 0 &amp; 2 \\
          3 &amp; -1 &amp; 2
        \end{pmatrix}
        \quad
        B =
        \begin{pmatrix}
          -7 &amp; 0 &amp; 5 \\
          3 &amp; 0 &amp; -2 \\
          10 &amp; 0 &amp; 3
        \end{pmatrix}
        </me>
      </p>

      <p></p> <!-- put in as a separator-->

      <p>
        <me>
        C =
        \begin{pmatrix}
          1 &amp; 2 &amp; 3 \\
          7 &amp; 14 &amp; 21 \\
          5 &amp; 10 &amp; 15
        \end{pmatrix}
        \quad 
        D =
        \begin{pmatrix}
          0 &amp; 0 &amp; 0 \\
          2 &amp; 0 &amp; 2 \\
          3 &amp; -1 &amp; 2
        \end{pmatrix}
        </me>
      </p>
    </li>

  </ul>
</handout>